<p><strong>Gura</strong> is an <strong>iterator-oriented</strong> programming language
that focuses on iterators with improved functions for calculation and data processing.
It makes you be able to write an artificial code for
what used to need a lot of codes of repeat syntax.</p>

<p>For detail, see descriptions in
<a href="en/ImplicitMapping.html" class="user-mention">Implicit-mapping</a>
and
<a href="en/MemberMapping.html" class="user-mention">Member-mapping</a>.</p>

<p><strong>Gura</strong> has a variety of functions for convinient use of computers such as
<a href="en/ImageProcessing.html" class="user-mention">graphic image processing</a>,
<a href="en/GUI.html" class="user-mention">GUI operation</a>,
<a href="en/HttpAccess.html" class="user-mention">HTTP access</a>,
<a href="en/DatabaseAccess.html" class="user-mention">database access</a>,
text operations like regular expression and CSV, etc.
As for handling data exchanged among those functions,
<a href="en/ImplicitMapping.html" class="user-mention">Implicit-mapping</a>
and
<a href="en/MemberMapping.html" class="user-mention">Member-mapping</a>
would process them in a effective way.</p>

<p><strong>Gura</strong> has a simple and easily-extensible syntax.
It has a mechanism of <a href="en/Argument.html" class="user-mention">variable-length arguments and named argument</a>,
and a flexible manner of parameter passing by <a href="en/Block.html" class="user-mention">block expression</a>.
Further more, with <a href="en/Quoted.html" class="user-mention">Quoted-values</a>,
you can create your original control statements by passing pre-evaluated expressions to functions.
You can also add member functions or variables to already existing classes and instances.
Please enjoy a world of meta-programming!</p>

<p><strong>Gura</strong> supports multi platforms.
Gura program written for Windows can run on Linux without any modification,
and opposite is also possible. How to install the package is described in
<a href="en/Install.html" class="user-mention">here</a>.
</p>

<p><strong>Gura</strong> is a language that can be expanded according to your usage.
If you find any lacking functions, you can create binary modules that run in native mode using C++.
I'm quite sure you'd recognize doing so is much easier than any specification
that other languages prepare for the similar purpose.
How to create such a module is described in <a href="en/BinaryModule.html" class="user-mention">here</a>.
</p>

